'''Nils Henrik Bruun''' (1832 in [[Tønsberg]] – 1916) was a [[Norway|Norwegian]] [[engineer]].

Educated at [[Chalmers University of Technology|Chalmers]] in Gothenburg, and in Germany, Bruun moved to Bergen in 1863 where he engaged in several engineering ventures; he and [[Peter Jebsen]] founded the factories in [[Dale, Hordaland|Dale]], and later he engages in mining in [[Stord]] and [[Karmøy]]. He received the contract to build the tunnels on [[Vossebanen]] in 1875.<ref name=gubberud>{{cite book |first=Ivar J. |last=Gubberud |title=Vossebanen 1883-1983 |year=1983 |publisher=Norsk Jernbaneklubb |location=Oslo |isbn=82-90286-05-8 |page=14}}</ref> During the 1880s he was director of [[Bergen Mekaniske Verksted]], and in 1898 he bought half the rights to the waterfalls in [[Øvre Årdal]], selling them to [[BASF]] in 1906. He was awarded the [[Order of St. Olav]] in 1894.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nrk.no/distrikt/sogn_og_fjordane/fylkesleksikon/1517840.html |title=Nils Henrik Bruun |author=[[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation]] |date=2001-12-18}}</ref>

