{{for|the composition by Karlheinz Stockhausen|Spiel (Stockhausen)}} [[File:Essen 2008 50120.jpg|thumb|Spiel 2008]] '''Internationale Spieltage SPIEL''', often called the '''Essen Game Fair''' after the city where it is held, is an annual four-day [[boardgame]] [[trade fair]] which is also open to the public held in October<ref name="Economist2015">{{cite web |url=https://www.economist.com/news/business/21669930-table-top-games-are-booming-video-game-age-not-twilight-sunrise |title=Not twilight, but sunrise. Table-top games are booming in the video-game age |work=The Economist |date=2015-10-03 |accessdate=2015-10-29}}</ref> (Thursday to the following Sunday) at the [[Messe Essen]] exhibition centre in [[Essen]]. With 1,021 exhibitors from 50 nations (in 2016) SPIEL is the worldwide biggest fair for [[board game|board games]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/oct/31/board-gamers-germany-essen-spiel-exhibition|title=For board gamers, heaven is a place on earth – located in Germany|last=Duffy|first=Owen|date=2015-10-31|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|access-date=2016-11-11}}</ref> Many new games are released at the fair each year, especially (but not exclusively) [[European-style board game]]s.
[[File:Messe-Essen-Eingang-Sued-2016.jpg|thumb|Messe Essen, the event venue]] At SPIEL board games are offered which are hard to find in retail because a lot of international and small exhibitors present their products. While the prices for buying the games at the fair do not tend to be significantly lower than those in retail, the games are typically available sooner than in regular board game shops, come with promotional materials (mostly extra cards or tokens with a few more game mechanics, but also T-shirts and similar merchandise) and it is an occasion where passionate board gamers can meet and chat with [[Game design|game designers]], illustrators, and famous game reviewers.{{Citation needed|date=November 2016}}
The fair began in 1983.<ref name="Woods2012">{{cite book|author=Stewart Woods|title=Eurogames: The Design, Culture and Play of Modern European Board Games|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GPdRVOl8fU0C&pg=PA64|date=16 August 2012|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-6797-6|page=64}}</ref>
